{"title_page": "Leslie Jordan", "text_new": "{{short description|American actor}}\n\n{{Infobox person\n| name          = Leslie Jordan\n| image         = lesliejordan.jpg\n| caption        = Jordan in 2007\n| birthname     = Leslie Allen Jordan\n| birth_date    = {{birth date and age|1955|4|29}}\n| birth_place   = [[Chattanooga, Tennessee]], United States<ref>[http://thelesliejordan.com/site/bio/ Biography] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140407092451/http://thelesliejordan.com/site/bio/ |date=2014-04-07 }} at Leslie Jordan's official website</ref> \n| occupation    = Actor, playwright\n| yearsactive   = 1986\u2013present\n| height        = {{convert|4|ft|11|in|m}}<ref name=\":1\" />\n| website       =\n}}\n\n'''Leslie Allen Jordan''' (born April 29, 1955) is an American [[actor]] and [[playwright]]. He is best known for his roles as Lonnie Garr in ''[[Hearts Afire]]'', Beverley Leslie in ''[[Will & Grace]]'' and several characters in the ''[[American Horror Story]]'' franchise. One of his best-known onstage performances was in ''[[Sordid Lives]]'', where he played Earl \"Brother Boy\" Ingram, a role he took to the big screen in the popular [[cult film]] of the same name.\n\n== Early life ==\n\nLeslie Jordan was born in [[Chattanooga, Tennessee]].<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url = http://www.tv.com/people/leslie-jordan/biography/|title = Leslie Jordan Biography|date = |accessdate = |website = TV.com |publisher = |last = |first = }}</ref> In a 2014 interview, Jordan said that he had a difficult time growing up [[Southern Baptist Church|Southern Baptist]]. \"I was baptized 14 times. Every time the preacher would say, 'Come forward, sinners!' I\u2019d say 'Oooh, I was out in the woods with that boy, I better go forward.'\"<ref>{{Cite web|url = http://www.phillymag.com/g-philly/2014/03/12/girl-talk-gossiping-southern-baptist-sissies-star-leslie-jordan/|title = GIRL TALK: Gossiping With Southern Baptist Sissies Star Leslie Jordan |date = 12 March 2014|accessdate = October 13, 2014|website = Philly Magazine|publisher = |last = Middleton|first = Josh}}</ref>\n\nDuring an appearance on'' [[Today (U.S. TV program)|Today]]'' with [[Hoda Kotb]] and [[Kathie Lee Gifford]], Jordan discussed his personal life and career. He described his mother, Peggy Ann, as being supportive and accepting though never truly understanding him. When asked about his mother, he said she lives in Chattanooga and is a private woman. Jordan's father was a lieutenant colonel in the United States Army and died in a plane crash when Jordan was 11 years old.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\nJordan moved to [[Los Angeles]] in 1982 where he became involved with drugs and alcohol and was arrested several times. When Jordan was 17 years old, he began to journal daily, which helped him recover from drug and alcohol abuse.<ref>{{Cite news|url = http://www.isthmus.com/arts/article.php?article=38022|title = Funnyman Leslie Jordan reflects on 'The Help', 'Will & Grace', 'Ski Patrol' and one-man comedy shows| last = Duerst |first = Austin |date = 16 October 2012|website = isthmus.com |accessdate = 31 July 2015}}</ref> In 2010, Jordan told talk show host [[Wendy Williams]] that he had been sober for thirteen years.<ref name=\"youtube.com\">{{Cite news|url = https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=U-h8GEvRQlU|title = \"Leslie Jordan's Famous Prison Mate,\" ''The Wendy Williams Show''|date = 20 April 2010|website = youtube.com |accessdate = 1 October 2019}}</ref> In the same appearance Jordan said that before he gave up drinking, he once shared a cell with [[Robert Downey Jr.]], and when they both appeared later on ''[[Ally McBeal]]'', Downey couldn't quite place where they had met before.<ref name=\"youtube.com\"/>\n\nEarly in the AIDS crisis, Jordan became involved in [[AIDS Project Los Angeles]] (APLA) as a buddy and as a food delivery person for [[Project Angel Food]].<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n== Career ==\n\nJordan is recognizable for his diminutive size and Southern drawl.<ref name=\":1\" /> He appeared as newspaper editor Mr. Blackly in the movie ''[[The Help (film)|The Help]]''.<ref>{{Cite news|url = http://chattanoogan.com/2012/2/19/219837/Emmy-Winner-Leslie-Jordan-Headlines.aspx|title = Emmy-Winner Leslie Jordan Headlines Tuesday Night Live May 15|last = |first = |date = |work = |accessdate = }}</ref> His television career includes guest appearances on ''[[Murphy Brown]]'', ''[[Will & Grace]]'', ''[[Lois & Clark: The New Adventures of Superman]]'', ''[[Star Trek: Voyager]]'', ''[[Caroline in the City]]'', ''[[Pee-Wee's Playhouse]]'', ''[[Reba (TV series)|Reba]]'', ''[[Boston Public]]'', ''[[Boston Legal]]'', ''[[Nash Bridges]]'', ''[[American Horror Story]]'' and ''[[Hearts Afire]]''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://ew.com/movies/leslie-jordan-the-help-cast-rescued-puppy/|title=Leslie Jordan reveals how 'The Help' cast rescued a puppy \u2014 and who they named it after|website=EW.com|language=EN|access-date=2020-04-02}}</ref> He guest-starred on the [[comedy-drama]] ''[[Ugly Betty]]'' as celebrity-trasher Quincy Combs. In 2007, Jordan starred as Jesse Joe in the short-lived [[The CW Television Network|CW]] television program ''[[Hidden Palms]],'' and portrayed the ski patrol director in ''[[Ski Patrol (1990 film)|Ski Patrol]]''.<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.today.com/popculture/leslie-jordan-s-instagram-videos-are-beacon-funny-t177193|title='Will & Grace' actor's viral videos are a beacon of funny in the darkness|website=TODAY.com|language=en|access-date=2020-04-02}}</ref>\n\nOn the television series ''Will & Grace,'' Jordan played [[Karen Walker (character)|Karen]]'s pretentious, sexually ambiguous rival [[Supporting characters on Will & Grace|Beverley Leslie]]<ref name=Atlanta /> for which he received an [[Emmy Award]] for Best Guest Actor in a Comedy Series at the [[58th Annual Primetime Emmy Awards]] in 2006. His [[Emmy Award]] earned him an invitation to present the awards for Outstanding Writing for a Comedy Series and Outstanding Directing for a Comedy Series at the 2006 Emmy Awards with [[Cloris Leachman]] a week later.<ref>{{Cite book|title = My Trip Down the Pink Carpet|last = Jordan|first = Leslie|publisher = Simon and Schuster| year = 2008|isbn = |location = |pages = }}</ref>\n\nJordan starred in the [[Television pilot|pilot]] episode of ''[[Laugh Out]]'', the world's first interactive, gay-themed comedy show.<ref name=Atlanta>{{cite press release| url= http://www.prnewswire.com/news-releases/atlanta-entertainment-company-to-produce-innovative-interactive-gay-themed-comedy-show-55898972.html |title= Atlanta Entertainment Company to Produce Innovative, Interactive Gay-Themed Comedy Show| website= prnewswire.com| date= 2 May 2015| location= Atlanta| accessdate= 31 July 2015}}</ref> On August 18, 2014, Jordan became a housemate in the [[Celebrity Big Brother 14|celebrity edition]] of the British reality game show'' [[Big Brother (UK)|Big Brother]]''. He was the second person to leave the Big Brother house (August 29, 2014). In January 2015, Jordan guest starred in the British sitcom ''[[Benidorm (TV series)|Benidorm]]'' for two episodes as the character \"Buck-A-Roo\".\n\nJordan is an accomplished stage actor and playwright. In one of his best-known performances onstage, he played Earl \"Brother Boy\" Ingram in ''[[Sordid Lives]]'', a role he took to the big screen in the popular [[cult film]] of the same name. Jordan reprised the role in the ''[[Sordid Lives: The Series]]'', a televised spin-off of the movie airing on [[Logo (TV channel)|Logo]] where he plays a character that is in a mental hospital.<ref>{{cite news | first=Tim | last=Parks | title=The \u2018Sordid Lives\u2019 of \u2018Southern Baptist Sissies | url=http://www.gaylesbiantimes.com/?id=7957 | work=The Gay and Lesbian Times | date=17 August 2006 | accessdate=2008-04-08 | url-status=usurped | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080302204936/http://www.gaylesbiantimes.com/?id=7957 | archivedate=2 March 2008 }}</ref> He wrote and starred in the autobiographical play ''Lost in the Pershing Point Hotel'', which was also made into a motion picture.  He recently toured the country performing his one-man stage comedy, ''Like a Dog on Linoleum'', to generally favorable reviews.<ref>{{cite news | first= David C. |last= Nichols | title='Dog on Linoleum' finds firm footing | url=https://articles.latimes.com/2004/oct/15/entertainment/et-dog15 | work=Los Angeles Times | date=15 October 2004 | accessdate=2 April 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal\n| last         =Helbig\n| first        =Jack\n| date         =11 August 2005\n| title        =Like a Dog on Linoleum\n| url          =http://www.chicagoreader.com/chicago/like-a-dog-on-linoleum/Content?oid=919582\n| journal      =[[Chicago Reader]]\n| accessdate   =April 2, 2014\n}}</ref>\n\nJordan's first autobiographical stage show was called ''Hysterical Blindness and Other Southern Tragedies That Have Plagued My Life Thus Far'',<ref name=\":0\" /> with music and lyrics by [[Joe Patrick Ward]].<ref>{{cite magazine|url=https://books.google.ca/books?id=LMIBAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA97|page=97|title=Theatre Reviews|date=13 June 1994|magazine=New York Magazine|via=Google Books}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1994/05/28/theater/review-theater-a-hollywood-soul-s-trip-from-tennessee.html|title=Review/Theater; A Hollywood Soul's Trip From Tennessee|date=28 May 1994|website=The New York Times}}</ref>  The production, in which Jordan was backed by a gospel choir singing satirical songs about [[racism]] and [[homophobia]], was produced off-Broadway at the [[SoHo Playhouse]] and ran for seven months. Next, he distilled his experiences growing up as an effeminate, tiny boy in the [[Southern United States]] and in show business into an autobiographical one-man show, ''My Trip Down the Pink Carpet''. During the opening of ''My Trip Down the Pink Carpet'', Jordan's microphone stopped working, but he kept on with the show like nothing happened, and his show was a success.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite journal|url = http://go.galegroup.com/ps/retrieve.do?sgHitCountType=None&sort=RELEVANCE&inPS=true&prodId=AONE&userGroupName=tel_a_utc&tabID=T002&searchId=R11&resultListType=RESULT_LIST&contentSegment=&searchType=AdvancedSearchForm&currentPosition=1&contentSet=GALE%7CA195465905&&docId=GALE&#124;A195465905&docType=GALE&role=|title = Leslie Jordan: from small screen to big stage|last = Freeman|first = Chris|date = 2009|journal = |accessdate = |doi = |pmid = }}</ref> After touring the nation for several months with the production, the show opened off-Broadway at the [[Midtown Theater]] on April 19, 2010.  The show is produced by Jordan's friend, actress [[Lily Tomlin]]. Jordan announced on ''[[The Paul O'Grady Show]]'' that he will be bringing his show to London's [[Apollo Theatre]].\n\nOn November 1, 2017, Jordan appeared in the new British television drama ''[[Living the Dream (UK TV series)|Living the Dream]]'' produced jointly by [[Sky UK|Sky]] and [[Big Talk Productions]] but branded as a Sky Original Production.<ref name= \"florida\">{{cite news |last=Dowell |first=Ben |url= http://www.radiotimes.com/news/2017-10-19/philip-glenister-and-lesley-sharp-are-brits-abroad-in-first-look-at-skys-new-florida-comedy-living-the-dream/ |title=Philip Glenister and Lesley Sharp are Brits abroad in first look at Sky\u2019s new Florida comedy Living the Dream |work=[[Radio Times]] |date=October 19, 2017 |accessdate=February 16, 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn the fall of 2018, Jordan starred in the [[Fox network]] sitcom ''[[The Cool Kids (TV series)|The Cool Kids]]'', along with [[Martin Mull]], [[Vicki Lawrence]] and [[David Alan Grier]].<ref>{{cite news|last=Boedeker|first=Hal|url=http://www.orlandosentinel.com/entertainment/tv/tv-guy/os-et-fox-makes-room-for-veteran-performers-20180514-story.html|title=Fox makes room for veteran performers|newspaper=Orlando Sentinel|date=May 14, 2018|accessdate=May 15, 2018}}</ref>\n\nAs of April 2020, Jordan has 1,000,000 Instagram followers. He celebrated this by making a video wearing sunglasses and a fancy little suit for his followers. His following grew by 400,000 in one week during the coronavirus crisis.<ref name=\":2\" />\n\nOn April 2, 2020, Jordan will play the lead role of Phil in the Fox sitcom ''[[Call Me Kat]]'', along with [[Mayim Bialik]], [[Swoosie Kurtz]], [[Kyla Pratt]] and [[Cheyenne Jackson]].<ref>{{cite web |last=Petski|first=Denise|title=Leslie Jordan Joins \u2018Call Me Kat\u2019 Fox Comedy Series Starring Mayim Bialik|url=https://deadline.com/2020/04/leslie-jordan-call-me-kat-fox-comedy-series-mayim-bialik-1202898845/|website=Deadline Hollywood|accessdate=April 2, 2020 |language=en |date=April 2, 2020}}</ref>\n\n== Personal life ==\nJordan is gay and lives in [[Chattanooga, Tennessee]].<ref>https://www.newyorker.com/culture/culture-desk/leslie-jordan-perfectly-loopy-quarantine-videos</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Butterworth |first1=Benjamin |title=GT Icons \u2013 Will and Grace, Leslie Jordan |url=https://www.gaytimes.co.uk/culture/20716/gt-icons-will-and-grace-leslie-jordan/ |publisher=Gay Times |accessdate=5 April 2020 |date=26 December 2015}}</ref> He has been in several long term relationships.\n\n== Credits ==\n\n=== Writer ===\n* ''Lost in the Pershing Point Hotel'' (play)\n* ''My Trip Down the Pink Carpet'' (2008)\n* ''Hysterical Blindness and Other Southern Tragedies That Have Plagued My Life Thus Far''\n\n=== Stage ===\n* ''Found a Peanut'' (1986)<ref name=\"LAT 19860701\">{{Cite web |url=https://articles.latimes.com/1986-07-01/entertainment/ca-819_1_dead-bird |title=Stage Review : 'Found A Peanut' As Child's Play |work=[[Los Angeles Times]] |date=1 July 1986 |accessdate=October 31, 2013 |last=Drake |first=Sylvie}}</ref>\n* ''Sordid Lives'' (1996)\n* ''[[Southern Baptist Sissies]]''\n* ''Lost in the Pershing Point Hotel''\n* ''Like a Dog on Linoleum'' (2004)\n* ''My Trip Down the Pink Carpet'' (2010)\n* ''[[Lucky Guy (musical)|Lucky Guy]]'' 