957|location=New York|publisher=Scribner|oclc=425613}} Seven volume scholarly biography, winner of the Pulitzer Prize.  Volumes 3\u20135 cover the Revolutionary War period.\n*{{cite book|last=Freeman|first=Douglas S|author2=Harwell, Richard |title=Washington|url=https://archive.org/details/washington00free|url-access=registration|year=1968|location=New York|publisher=Scribner|oclc=426557}} Abridgement of Freeman's multivolume biography.\n*{{Cite book|last=Furneaux|first=Rupert|title=The Battle of Saratoga|location=New York|publisher=Stein and Day|ref=Furneaux|year=1971|isbn=978-0-8128-1305-0|oclc=134959}}\n*{{cite book|last=Grizzard|first=Frank E., Jr|authorlink=Frank E. Grizzard, Jr.|title=George! A Guide to All Things Washington|location=Buena Vista and Charlottesville, VA|publisher=Mariner Publishing|year=2005|isbn=978-0-9768238-0-3|oclc=232006080}}\n*{{Cite book|last=Gruber|first=Ira|title=The Howe Brothers and the American Revolution|publisher=Atheneum Press|location=New York|year=1972|oclc=1464455|isbn=978-0-8078-1229-7}}\n*{{cite book|last=Higginbotham|first=Don|authorlink=Don Higginbotham|title=George Washington and the American Military Tradition|year=1985|publisher=University of Georgia Press|location=Athens, GA|isbn=978-0-8203-0786-2|oclc=489783125|url=https://archive.org/details/georgewashington00higg}}\n*{{cite book|last=Higginbotham|first=Don|title=George Washington: Uniting a Nation|year=2004|publisher=Rowman and Littlefield|location=Lanham, MD|isbn=978-0-7425-2209-1|oclc=60832326}}\n*{{cite book|last=Johnston|first=Henry Phelps|title=The Campaign of 1776 Around New York and Brooklyn|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=cVAOAAAAIAAJ&printsec=frontcover|location=Brooklyn, NY|publisher=Long Island Historical Society|year=1878|oclc=234710}}\n*{{cite book|title=The Winter Soldiers|first=Richard M|last=Ketchum|publisher=Doubleday|location=Garden City, NY|isbn=0-385-05490-4|year=1973|oclc=640266|url=https://archive.org/details/wintersoldiers00ketc}}\n*{{cite book|last=Larrabee|first=Harold A|title=Decision at the Chesapeake|publisher=Clarkson N. Potter|location=New York|year=1964|oclc=426234}}\n*{{cite book|last=Leckie|first=Robert|authorlink=Robert Leckie (author)|title=George Washington's War: The Saga of the American Revolution|location=New York|publisher=HarperCollins|year=1993|isbn=978-0-06-092215-3|ref=Leckie|oclc=29748139}}\n*{{cite book|last=Lengel|first=Edward|authorlink=Edward G. Lengel|title=General George Washington |url=https://archive.org/details/generalgeorgewas00leng|url-access=registration|location=New York|publisher=Random House Trade Paperbacks |year=2005|isbn=978-0-8129-6950-4|oclc=255642134}}\n*{{cite book|last=Linder|first=Bruce|title=Tidewater's Navy: an Illustrated History|publisher=Naval Institute Press|year=2005|location=Annapolis, MD|isbn=978-1-59114-465-6|oclc=60931416}}\n*{{cite book|last=Martin|first=James Kirby|authorlink=James Kirby Martin|year=1997|title=Benedict Arnold: Revolutionary Hero (An American Warrior Reconsidered)|publisher=New York University Press|location=New York|isbn=0-8147-5560-7|oclc=36343341|ref=Martin|url=https://archive.org/details/benedictarnoldre0000mart}}\n*{{cite book | last = McCullough | first = David | authorlink =David McCullough | title = [[1776 (book)|1776]] | publisher =Simon and Schuster Paperback| year = 2005 |ref=McCullough |isbn=0-7432-2672-0 }} 386 pp. very well written overview of the year in America\n*{{cite book| last=Morelock|first=Jerry D|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=q54NDbdVmJMC&pg=PA69&lpg=PA69&resnum=4#PPA53,M1| chapter=Washington as Strategist| title=Compound Warfare| pages=53\u201389| publisher=DIANE Publishing| year=2002| isbn=978-1-4289-1090-4 }}\n*{{cite book | last = Nelson | first = James | authorlink = James L. Nelson | title = George Washington's Secret Navy | publisher = McGraw-Hill | location = New York | year = 2008 | isbn = 0-07-149389-1 | url-access = registration | url = https://archive.org/details/georgewashington0000nels }}\n*{{cite book|last=O'Meara|first=Walter|authorlink=Walter O'Meara|title=Guns at the Forks|url=https://archive.org/details/gunsatforks0000omea|url-access=registration|publisher=Prentice Hall|location=Englewood Cliffs, NJ|year=1965|oclc=21999143}}\n*{{cite book|last=Randall|first=Willard Sterne|authorlink=Willard Sterne Randall|year=1990|title=Benedict Arnold: Patriot and Traitor|publisher=William Morrow|location=New York|isbn=978-1557100344|oclc=185605660|ref=Randall|url=https://archive.org/details/benedictarnoldpa00rand_0}}\n*{{cite book|last=Randall|first=Willard Sterne|title=George Washington: A Life|publisher=Henry Holt|year=1998|location=New York|isbn=978-0-8050-5992-2|oclc=40343114|url=https://archive.org/details/georgewashington00will_1}}\n*{{cite book|last=Schecter|first=Barton|title=The Battle for New York|publisher=Walker|location=New York|year=2002|isbn=0-8027-1374-2|ref=Schecter|url=https://archive.org/details/battlefornewyork00sche|oclc=50658296|url-status=dead}}\n*{{cite book|last=Ward|first=Christopher|title=War of the Revolution|url=https://archive.org/details/warofrevolution00ward|url-access=registration|publisher=Macmillan|location=New York|year=1952|oclc=214962727}}\n*{{cite book|last=Wickwire|first=Franklin and Mary|title=Cornwallis: The American Adventure|url=https://archive.org/details/cornwallisameric00wick|url-access=registration|location=Boston|publisher=Houghton Mifflin|year=1970|oclc=62690}}\n{{refend}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* Billias, George Athan, ed., ''George Washington's Generals'' pp 3-21.\n* Bill, Alfred Hoyt. ''The Campaign of Princeton, 1776-1777'' (1948).\n* Bliven. Bruce, Jr. '' Under the Guns: New York, 1775-1776'' (1972).\n* Bodle, Wayne. ''The Valley Forge Winter: Civilians and Soldiers in War'' (2002).\n* Carp, E. Wayne. ''To Starve the Army at Pleasure: Continental Army Administration and American Political Culture, 1775\u20131783.'' (U of North Carolina Press, 1984). \n* Cox, Caroline. ''A Proper Sense of Honor: Service and Sacrifice in George Washington\u2019s Army'' (2004)\n* Dwyer, William M. ''The Day is Ours! November 1776-January 1777:An Inside View of the Battles of Trenton and Princeton'' (1983).\n* Ferling, John. ''Almost a Miracle: The American Victory in the War of Independence'' (2007) [https://www.questia.com/library/117312318/almost-a-miracle-the-american-victory-in-the-war online]\n* Flynn, Matthew J., and Stephen E. Grffin. ''Washington and Napoleon: Leadership in the Age of Revolution'' (Potomac Books, 2012).\n* Freeman, Douglas Southall. ''Washington'' (1995) 896pp; Abridged version of his Pulitzer prize-winning seven volume Biography; vol 4-5-6 cover the war years. [https://www.amazon.com/Washington-Douglas-Southall-Freeman/dp/0684826372/ excerpt]\n* Higginbotham, Don. ''George Washington and the American Military Tradition'' (U of Georgia Press, 1987).\n* Higginbotham, Don. \"American Historians and the Military History of the American Revolution.\" ''American Historical Review'' 70.1 (1964): 18\u201334.\n* Higginbotham, Don. \"Essay Review: The Washington Theme in Recent Historical Literature.\" (1990): 423\u2013437. [https://journals.psu.edu/pmhb/article/viewFile/44589/44310 online]\n* Kwasny, Mark V. ''Washington's Partisan War, 1775-1783'' (1996) [https://www.questia.com/library/100898981/washington-s-partisan-war-1775-1783 online]\n* Laver, Harry S. and Jeffrey J. Matthews, eds. ''The Art of Command: Military Leadership from George Washington to Colin Powell'' (2008) pp 11\u201332. [https://www.questia.com/library/120079810/the-art-of-command-military-leadership-from-george  online]\n* McCullough, David. ''1776'' (2005)\n* Neimeyer, Charles Patrick. ''America Goes to War: A Social History of the Continental Army'' (1995) [https://www.jstor.org/stable/j.ctt9qg7q2 complete text online]\n* Orr III, Lt-Colonel Alan L. \"George Washington: America's First Strategic Leader\" (U.S. Army War College, 2007) [http://www.dtic.mil/dtic/tr/fulltext/u2/a468988.pdf online].\n* Palmer, Dave Richard. ''The Way of the Fox: American Strategy in the War for America, 1775-1783'' (1975) \n* Risch, Erna. ''Supplying Washington's Army'' (Center of Military History, 1981).\n* Royster, Charles. ''A Revolutionary People at War: The Continental Army and American Character, 1775-1783'' (1979)\n* Stillings, Kris J. \"Washington and the Formulation of American Strategy for the War of Independence\" (U.S. Marine Corps Staff and Command College, 2001) [https://archive.org/details/DTIC_ADA401347 online]\n* Whiteley, Emily Stone. ''Washington and his Aides-de-Camp'' (1936)\n* Wright, Esmond. ''Washington and the American Revolution'' (1962), brief and scholarly.\n\n===Espionage===\n* Harty, Jared B. \"George Washington: Spymaster and General Who Saved the American Revolution\" (Staff paper,  No. ATZL-SWV. Army Command And General Staff College Fort Leavenworth, School Of Advanced Military Studies, 2012) [http://www.dtic.mil/get-tr-doc/pdf?AD=ADA566174 online].\n* Kilmeade, Brian, and Don Yaeger. ''George Washington's Secret Six: The Spy Ring that Saved the American Revolution'' (Penguin, 2016).\n* Mahoney, Harry Thayer, and Marjorie Locke Mahoney. ''Gallantry in action: A biographic dictionary of espionage in the American revolutionary war'' (University Press of America, 1999).\n* Misencik, Paul R. ''Sally Townsend, George Washington's Teenage Spy'' (McFarland, 2015).\n* O'Toole, George J.A. ''Honorable Treachery: A History of US Intelligence, Espionage, and Covert Action from the American Revolution to the CIA'' (2nd ed. 2014), ch 1\u20135.\n* Rose, Alexander. ''Washington's Spies: The Story of America's First Spy Ring'' (2006), focuses on the Culper Ring.\n* Van Doren, Carl. ''Secret History of the American Revolution: An Account of the Conspiracies of Benedict Arnold and Numerous Others Drawn from the Secret Service'' (1941) [https://archive.org/details/secrethistoryofa00vand online free]\n\n{{George Washington}}\n{{Continental Army}}\n{{American Revolutionary War|state=collapsed}}\n\n{{Good article}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Revolution, George Washington In The American}}\n[[Category:George Washington|Revolutionary War]]\n[[Category:American Revolutionary War|Washington]]\n[[Category:Military careers by individual|Washington 3<!--1: Military career of; 2: GW in the FandI War-->]]\n", "name_user": "2601:240:db7f:cf16:380c:f6bd:5b4b:bb87", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/George_Washington_in_the_American_Revolution"}
{"title_page": "List of kakapo", "text_new": "{{short description|Wikipedia list article}}\n[[File:Strigops habroptilus 1.jpg|thumb|right|Female k\u0101k\u0101p\u014d Pura on [[Codfish Island]]]]\nEvery known living '''[[kakapo|k\u0101k\u0101p\u014d]]''', except some young chicks, has been given a name by [[Kakapo Recovery Programme|K\u0101k\u0101p\u014d Recovery Programme]] officials. Many of the older birds were given [[English language]] names, but more recent chicks have been given [[M\u0101ori language|M\u0101ori]] names. Some k\u0101k\u0101p\u014d, such as Richard Henry and Moorhouse, are named after people who have provided assistance to the preservation efforts. A k\u0101k\u0101p\u014d interactive family tree is available.<ref>{{cite web |title=The K\u0101k\u0101p\u014d |url=https://public.tableau.com/views/TheKakapo/Dashboard1?:embed=y&:display_count=yes&:toolbar=no&:showVizHome=no}}</ref>\n{{TOC right}}\n\n==Recent population changes==\nAfter a good breeding year in 2002, the population remained at 86 until 2004, when three two-year-old female k\u0101k\u0101p\u014d died from infections by the soil bacterium ''[[Erysipelas]]''.<ref name=\"illness\">{{cite press release|title=Kakapo illness identified |url=http://www.biodiversity.govt.nz/news/media/current/13jul04.html |date=13 July 2004 |publisher=Biodiversity Information Online, New Zealand Government |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20081014070022/http://www.biodiversity.govt.nz/news/media/current/13jul04.html | archivedate = 14 October 2008 | url-status = dead }}</ref><ref name=\"Gartrell\">B. D. Gartrell; M. R. Alley; H. Mack; J. Donald; K. McInnes; and P. Jansen (2005). Erysipelas in the critically endangered kakapo (Strigops habroptilus). ''Avian Pathology'', 34 (5), 383\u2013387. {{doi|10.1080/03079450500268583}}.</ref> Four chicks survived from the 2005 breeding season. The male Gunner died of [[aflatoxicosis]] during the New Zealand winter of 2005, bringing the population back to 86.<ref>Merton, D. (2005). [http://www.parrots.org/pdfs/our_publications/psittascene/2005/05May63.pdf Kakapo update 2005]. ''PsittaScene'', 17 (2), 7\u20139.</ref> In April 2008, the population grew to 93<ref>{{cite web|title=World kakapo population rises by five|url=http://www.nzherald.co.nz/section/1/story.cfm?c_id=1&objectid=10501192|date=31 March 2008|work=NZ Herald|accessdate=2008-03-31}}</ref> with the hatching of seven chicks,<ref name=\"KRP 2008-04-08\">{{cite web|url=http://www.kakaporecovery.org.nz/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=158:all-eggs-hatched&catid=53:ranger-diaries&Itemid=207 |title=Ranger's Diaries: All eggs hatched |publisher=Kakapo Recovery Programme |date=2008-04-08 |accessdate=2008-04-12}}</ref> then fell to 92 due to the death of adult Bill.<ref name=\"KRP 2008-04-01\">{{cite web|url=http://www.kakaporecovery.org.nz/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=155:more-chicks&catid=53:ranger-diaries&Itemid=207 |title=Ranger's Diaries: More chicks, but we've lost our friend Bill |publisher=Kakapo Recovery Progr04-01 |accessdate=2008-04-12}}</ref> One of the seven 2008 chicks died soon after hatching,<ref name=\"KRP 2008-03-24\">{{cite web|url=http://www.kakaporecovery.org.nz/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=153:sadness-at-easter&catid=53:ranger-diaries&Itemid=207 |title=Ranger's Diaries: Sadness at Easter |publisher=Kakapo Recovery Programme |date=2008-03-24 |accessdate=2008-04-12}}</ref> bringing the total down to 91, and on 28 October 2008, male Lee died, bringing the population down to 90.<ref name=\"KRP 2008-11-11\">{{cite web|url=http://www.kakaporecovery.org.nz/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=172:ranger-diaries&catid=53:ranger-diaries&Itemid=207 |title=Spring has sprung! |publisher=Kakapo Recovery Programme |date=2008-11-11 |accessdate=2008-11-15}}</ref> Male Rangi was rediscovered in February 2009 after spending 21 years living on Codfish Island.<ref name=\"KRP 2009-02-08\">{{cite news |url=http://www.stuff.co.nz/4841375a11.html |title=Kakapo back to nest after 21 years |author=Mussen, Deidre |date=5 March 2009 |work=[[The Sunday Star-Times]] |accessdate=15 October 2011}}</ref> The 2009 breeding season resulted in 33 chicks (20 male and 13 female), bringing the population up to 124.<ref name=\"124 Kakapo\">{{cite web|url=http://www.stuff.co.nz/southland-times/news/2416123/Another-chance-to-see-kakapo|title=Another chance to see kakapo |author=AMY MILNE|publisher=The Southland Times|date=2009-05-16}}</ref> A number of older birds died during 2010, followed by the significant loss of the only remaining [[Fiordland]] k\u0101k\u0101p\u014d, Richard Henry, announced during January 2011. His Fiordland genes survive through his three progeny.<ref name=\"richardhenry2010\">{{cite web|last=DOC|first=Media release|title=K\u0101k\u0101p\u014d males 'boom' on as legendary bird dies|url=http://www.doc.govt.nz/about-doc/news/media-releases/2011/kakapo-males-boom-on-as-legendary-bird-dies/|publisher=NZ Department of Conservation}}</ref>\nThe breeding season in 2011 produced 11 chicks (eight females, three male), which all survived, bringing the population to 131. However, the deaths of several birds followed and with no breeding season in 2012, the population dropped to 124.<ref name=\"recoveryprogrammefront\">{{cite web|url=http://www.kakaporecovery.org.nz/ |title=Home of the Kakapo Recovery Programme &#124; Kakapo Recovery Programme |publisher=Kakaporecovery.org.nz |date= |accessdate=2012-07-12}}</ref> As of May 2014, with the hatching of six eggs (the first hatchings since 2011) the total population had increased to 130 living individuals.\n\nForty-seven chicks hatched in the 2016 nesting season, making it a \"record breeding season\". As of July 2016, 34 of them had survived.<ref name=\"hatchingseason2016\">{{cite web|url=https://www.beehive.govt.nz/release/final-kakapo-egg-year-hatches |title=Final Kakpo egg of the year hatches |publisher=Kakaporecovery.org.nz |date= |accessdate=2016-06-09}}</ref><ref>{{cite tweet|user=takapodigs|author=Dr Andrew Digby|number=741787234110574593|date=12 June 2016|title=Another blow. #kakapo chick Zephyr2, 60d, has died. She was ill with respiratory condition and undergoing treatment.}}</ref>\n\nAs of January 2020, the New Zealand Dept of Conservation site showed a population of {{Number of Living Kakapo}}.\n\n== Living k\u0101k\u0101p\u014d ({{Number of Living Kakapo}}<!-- to update this number see link on the talk page -->) ==\n\n===Females (99)===\n[[File:Kakapo-population-size.svg|thumb|400px|Kakapo population development]]\n#'''Adelaide''' \u2013 hatched: 2016; mother: Kuia, father: Kumi.\n#'''\u1fb9io''' - hatched: 2019; mother: Mila, father: Horton.\n#'''Ako''' - hatched: 2019; mother: Esperance, father: Komaru.\n#'''Alice''' \u2013 first captured: 1981; mother of Snark '81, Manu '97; Al, Pearl '02, Huarangi, Vori, Whet\u016b \u201819.\n#'''Alison''' - hatched: 2019; mother: Queenie, father: Tutoko.\n#'''Aparima''' \u2013 hatched: 2002; mother: Wendy, father: Waynebo; mother of JEM '08, Bunker, Chicory, Sage, Horopito \u201819.\n#'''Aranga''' \u2013 hatched: 1999; mother: Lisa, father: Ox;{{cn|date=January 2017}} mother of Jack '09, Waikawa '11, Percy, Clout '16.<ref name=nestlist/>\n#'''\u0100ria''' \u2013 hatched: 2019; mother: Awarua, father: Komaru.\n#'''Atareta''' \u2013 hatched: 2011; mother: Lisa, father: Blades; mother of Manaaki, Atatu, Whaea Jane \u201819.\n#'''Atat\u016b''' - hatched 2019; mother: Atareta, father: Te Kingi.\n#'''Aumaria''' \u2013 hatched: 2016; mother: Stella, father: Blake.<ref name=\"blake\"/>\n#'''Awarua''' \u2013 hatched: 2009; mother: Kuihi, father: Barnard; mother of Motup\u014dhue, \u0100ria, Matariki '19.<ref name=nestlist>{{cite web|url=http://www.kakaporecovery.org.nz/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=137&Itemid=235| title=Kakapo Nesting Table|access-date=29 June 2010|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100604224131/http://www.kakaporecovery.org.